How kube-proxy Works with Services in Kubernetes

Whenever we create a Service inside the Kubernetes cluster, kube-proxy continuously watches the Service and Endpoint information from the API Server.

Flow Explanation
A Service is created in the cluster.
The API Server updates the Endpoint object based on which Pod is attached to the Service.
kube-proxy running on every node watches these changes.
kube-proxy creates iptables (or IPVS) rules on the node.
These rules forward incoming traffic to the correct Pod, even if the Pod is running on another node.
Request Flow Example


Client
   ↓
Node-1:30080   (NodePort Service)
   ↓
kube-proxy on Node-1
   ↓
iptables rules
   ↓
Traffic forwarded to Node-2
   ↓
Pod-A
Important Concept

Even if the request first reaches a node where the Pod is NOT running:

kube-proxy checks the Service endpoints.
It knows which node contains the actual Pod.
Using iptables rules, it forwards the traffic to the correct node and Pod.

So Kubernetes Services provide:

Load balancing
Service discovery
Cross-node traffic routing
Transparent networking between nodes and Pods
Simple One-Line Understanding

kube-proxy watches Services and Endpoints from the API Server and creates iptables rules to route user traffic to the correct Pod, even across different nodes.


